"Halldin S., Bergström H., Gustafsson D., Dahlgren L., Hjelm P., Lundin L.-C., Mellander P.-E., Nord T., Jansson P.-E., Seibert J., Stähli M., Szilágyi Kishné A., Smedman A.-S.","Continuous long-term measurements of soil-plant-atmosphere variables at an agricultural site",1999,"Agricultural and Forest Meteorology","98-99",,,"75","102",,,10.1016/S0168-1923(99)00149-5,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0033621491&partnerID=40&md5=651031a6c6cc9e97f75b2b4f9bd4b7e2","Dept. of Earth Sciences/Hydrology, Uppsala Univ., Villavagen 16, S., Uppsala, Sweden; Dept. of Earth Sciences/Meteorology, Uppsala Univ., Villavagen 16, S., Uppsala, Sweden; Department of Soil Sciences, Swed. Univ. Agric. Sci., P.O. B., Uppsala, Sweden; Dörby 3681, SE-386 96, Färjestaden, Sweden","Halldin, S., Dept. of Earth Sciences/Hydrology, Uppsala Univ., Villavagen 16, S., Uppsala, Sweden; Bergström, H., Dept. of Earth Sciences/Meteorology, Uppsala Univ., Villavagen 16, S., Uppsala, Sweden; Gustafsson, D., Department of Soil Sciences, Swed. Univ. Agric. Sci., P.O. B., Uppsala, Sweden; Dahlgren, L., Dörby 3681, SE-386 96, Färjestaden, Sweden; Hjelm, P., Dept. of Earth Sciences/Hydrology, Uppsala Univ., Villavagen 16, S., Uppsala, Sweden; Lundin, L.-C., Dept. of Earth Sciences/Hydrology, Uppsala Univ., Villavagen 16, S., Uppsala, Sweden; Mellander, P.-E., Dept. of Earth Sciences/Hydrology, Uppsala Univ., Villavagen 16, S., Uppsala, Sweden; Nord, T., Dept. of Earth Sciences/Hydrology, Uppsala Univ., Villavagen 16, S., Uppsala, Sweden; Jansson, P.-E., Department of Soil Sciences, Swed. Univ. Agric. Sci., P.O. B., Uppsala, Sweden; Seibert, J., Dept. of Earth Sciences/Hydrology, Uppsala Univ., Villavagen 16, S., Uppsala, Sweden; Stähli, M., Department of Soil Sciences, Swed. Univ. Agric. Sci., P.O. B., Uppsala, Sweden; Szilágyi Kishné, A., Dept. of Earth Sciences/Hydrology, Uppsala Univ., Villavagen 16, S., Uppsala, Sweden; Smedman, A.-S., Dept. of Earth Sciences/Meteorology, Uppsala Univ., Villavagen 16, S., Uppsala, Sweden","It is a major challenge in modern science to decrease the uncertainty in predictions of global climate change. One of the largest uncertainties in present-day global climate models resides with the understanding of processes in the soil-vegetation-atmosphere-transfer (SVAT) system. Continuous, long-term data are needed to correctly quantify balances of water, energy and CO2 in this system and to correctly model them. It is the objective of this paper to demonstrate how a combined system of existing sensor, computer, and network technologies could be set up to provide continuous and reliable long-term SVAT-process data from an agricultural site under almost all weather conditions. A long-term climate-monitoring system within the framework of NOPEX was set up in 1993-1994 at the Marsta Meteorological Observatory (MMO). It is situated in a flat agricultural area where annual crops are cultivated on a heavy clay soil. It has successfully monitored relevant states and fluxes in the system, such as atmospheric fluxes of momentum, heat, water vapour and CO2, atmospheric profiles of wind speed, direction, and temperature, short- and long-wave radiation, soil temperature, soil-water contents, groundwater levels, and rainfall and snow depth. System uptime has been more than 90% for most of its components during the first 5 years of operation. Results from the first 5 years of operation has proven MMO to be an ideal site for intercomparison and intercalibration of radiometers and fast turbulence sensors, and for evaluation of other sensors, e.g., rain gauges. The long time series of radiation data have been valuable to establish numerical limits for a set of quality-control flags. MMO has served as a boundary-layer research station and results from NOPEX campaigns show how the dimensionless wind gradient depends not only on the traditional stability parameter z/L but also on the height of the convective boundary layer. Measurements at the observatory grounds and a neighbouring field show a considerable variability in surface properties, which must be accounted for when assessing budgets of heat and other scalars. Questions concerning long-term calibration plans, maintenance of sensors and data-collection system, and continuous development of the computer network to keep it up to date are, however, only partly of interest as a research project in itself. It is thus difficult to get it funded from usual research-funding agencies. The full value of data generated by the MMO system can best be appreciated after a decade or more of continuous operation. Main uses of the data would be to evaluate how SVAT models handle the natural variability of climate conditions, quantification of water, carbon and energy budgets during various weather conditions, and development of new parameterisation schemes in global and regional climate models.","Energy balance; Evaporation; Heat flux; Intercalibration; Long term; Radiation; SVAT monitoring; Water balance","agricultural land; atmosphere-biosphere interaction; climate change; global climate; research program",,,,,,"Bergström, H., Radiosonde measurements at Marsta during CFE1 (1999) Agric. For. Meteorol., 98-99. , documented dataset on appended CD; Bergström, H., Högström, U., Calibration of a three-axial fiber-film system for meteorological turbulence measurements (1987) Dantec Information, 5, pp. 16-20; Bergström, H., Lundin, K., Climatological mean wind and turbulence measurements using a high quality cup anemometer system (1993) In: Proc. European Community Wing Energy Conference, pp. 697-700. , Lübeck-Travemünde, Germany, 8-12 March; Deheer-Amissah, A., Högström, U., Smedman-Högström, A.-S., Calculation of sensible and latent heat fluxes and surface resistance from profile data (1981) Boundary-Layer Meteorol., 20, pp. 35-49; Dehne, K., Bergholter, U., Kasten, F., (1993) IEA Comparison of Longwave Radiometers, , Report No. IEA-SHCP-9F-3, Deutscher Wetterdienst, Hamburg, 72 pp; Foken, T., Gryning, S.-E., Heikinheimo, M., Smedman, A.-S., (1994) Quality Assurance Plan for the NOPEX-Project Part 1. Comparison of Sensors for Scalars, , NOPEX Central Office, Uppsala, 20 pp; Foken, T., Handorf, D., Weisensee, U., Modell- und Meßkonzepte für das LITFASS-monitoring-Meßnetz (1997) Arbeitsergebnisse, 42. , Deutscher Wetterdienst Forschung und Entwickling, Offenbach, ISSN 1430-0281, 97 pp. (in German); Fröhlich, C., London, J., (1986) Revised Instruction Manual on Radiation Instruments and Measurements, , WCRP Publication No. 7, 140 pp; Gilgen, H.C., Whitlock, C., Koch, F., Müller, G., Ohmura, A., Steiger, D., Wheeler, R., (1995) Technical Plan for BSRN (Baseline Surface Radiation Network) Data Management, Version 2.1 (Final), , WMO/TD-No. 443, 57 pp; Omnidirectional (R3) & Assymetric (R3A) Research Ultrasonic Anemometer (1996) User Manual and Product Specification, , Gill Instruments Ltd. Doc. No. 1210-PS-0002-Issue 2. Lymington, Hampshire, U.K. 46 pp. +3 appendices; Gottschalk, L., Batchvarova, E., Frech, M., Gryning, S.E., Lindroth, A., Melas, D., Motovilov, Yu., Samuelsson, P., Scale aggregation - Comparison of flux estimates from NOPEX (1999) Agric. For. Meteorol., 98-99, pp. 103-119; Goulden, M.L., Munger, J.W., Fan, S.M., Daube, B.C., Wofsy, S.C., Exchange of carbon dioxide by a deciduous forest: Response to interannual climate variability (1996) Science, 271, pp. 1576-1578; Goulden, M.L., Munger, J.W., Fan, S.M., Daube, B.C., Wofsy, S.C., Measurements of carbon sequestration by long-term eddy-covariance methods and a critical evaluation of accuracy (1996) Global Change Biol., 2, pp. 169-182; Grelle, A., (1997) Long-term Water and Carbon Dioxide Fluxes from a Boreal Forest: Methods and Applications, , Doctoral thesis. Silvestria 28, Acta Universitatis Agriculturae Sueciae, 80 pp; Grelle, A., (1999), Personal communication. Department of Production Ecology, SLU, P.O. Box 7042, SE-750 07 Uppsala, Sweden, e-mail: Achim.Grelle@spek.slu